Suzukietal-AUC-analysis-Rscript

Area Under the Curve (AUC) analysis of bacterial growth by temperature

Code Adapted from Maier Lab growth curve analysis pipeline

# load libraries
pacman::p_load(readr, ggplot2, dplyr, gridExtra, xlsx, reshape, tidyr, gplots, fitdistrplus)
run_duration <- 23 # set run duration
plot_plots <- FALSE # indicate whether you want data to be plotted and saved
designation_for_control <- 37
# load files, scripts and annotations
Raw_Data_files <- list.files('Raw_Data')
Runs <- read.xlsx('Tab1.xlsx', 1, header=TRUE, stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
Layout <- read.xlsx('Tab2.xlsx', 1, header=TRUE, stringsAsFactors = FALSE)
strain_annotation <- read_csv('tax_table_maier.csv')

# Find out how many runs
Runs <- Runs[which(!is.na(Runs$Run)),] #in case it reads in funny
nr_runs <- as.numeric(Runs %>% dplyr::select(Run) %>% unique() %>% count())
nr_runs
## [1] 11
# Combine all Raw Data in a data.frame: 1) create an empty data.frame, 2) fill it

GCs <- data.frame(time=numeric(),
                  ID=integer(),
                  OD=numeric(), 
                  RRPPRCC=numeric(), 
                  design=character(), 
                  strain=character(), 
                  replicate=numeric(), 
                  position=numeric(), 
                  temperature=numeric()) # create a new dataframe with lots of empty columns

if(length(Raw_Data_files) == nr_runs) # Number of runs should match number of excel sheets
{
  
  for (i in 1:length(Raw_Data_files)){ # Loop through all the files
    run <-  strsplit(Raw_Data_files[i], 'Run')
    run <-  as.numeric(strsplit(run[[1]][2],'_')[[1]][1]) # From the file name, identify which run it is
    nr_plates <-  as.numeric(Runs %>% filter(Run == run) %>% dplyr::select(Plate) %>% unique() %>% count()) # From annotation file, identify the number of plates
    for (j in 1:nr_plates){ # Loop through all the plates of this run
      OD <- readOD96(paste0('Raw_Data/',Raw_Data_files[i]),j,run_duration) #read in excel sheet
      OD <- OD %>% mutate(RRPPRCC = run*100000+ID) #add identifier (Run, Run, Plate, Plate, Row, Column, Column)
      index <- which(Runs$Run==run & Runs$Plate==j) # find out index of lines to retrieve info on plate design, strain and replicate
      indexL <- which(Runs$Run==run & Runs$Plate==j & Runs$Half=='L') # left half only: find out index of lines to retrieve info on plate design, strain and replicate
      ODL <- OD %>% mutate(design = Runs$Design[indexL]) %>% mutate(strain = Runs$Strain[indexL]) %>% mutate(replicate = Runs$Replicate[indexL]) 
      ODL <- ODL %>% mutate(position = as.numeric(substr(ID, nchar(ID)-2, nchar(ID))))
      ODL <- left_join(ODL,Layout[which(Layout$Half=="L"),], by=c('design' ='design' , 'position' = 'position'))
      indexR <- which(Runs$Run==run & Runs$Plate==j & Runs$Half=='R') # right half only: find out index of lines to retrieve info on plate design, strain and replicate
      ODR <- OD %>% mutate(design = Runs$Design[indexR]) %>% mutate(strain = Runs$Strain[indexR]) %>% mutate(replicate = Runs$Replicate[indexL]) 
      ODR <- ODR %>% mutate(position = as.numeric(substr(ID, nchar(ID)-2, nchar(ID))))
      ODR <- left_join(ODR,Layout[which(Layout$Half=="R"),], by=c('design' ='design' , 'position' = 'position'))
      GCs <- bind_rows( GCs, ODL, ODR) # combine with other plates
      if(plot_plots)
      {
        title <- paste0('Run ', run, ' - ', 'Plate ', j,' - ', Runs$Strain[index], ' - Replicate ', Runs$Replicate[index]) # Title for the plots with Run Number and Plate Number
        myplot <- ggplot(OD,aes(time,OD))+geom_point()+facet_wrap(~ID,nrow=8,ncol=12)+theme_bw()+ggtitle(title) #plot the growth curves
        ggsave(filename=paste0('Plate_visualisation/',title,".pdf"), plot = myplot, device = 'pdf', width = 297, height = 210, units = "mm") #save the growth curves
      }
      
    }
  }
}else
{warning('Runs in overview and number of excel files are not matching')}

GCs <- GCs[which(!is.na(GCs$temperature)),]
GCs <- GCs[which(GCs$strain!="NT12097"),] #exclude a pathogenic E. coli (NT12097) - only commensal strains used for this analysis
# add a column for run and plate: RRPP 
GCs <- GCs %>% mutate(RRPP = as.numeric(substr(RRPPRCC, 1, nchar(RRPPRCC)-3))) 
GCs$RRPP <- paste(GCs$RRPP, GCs$Half, sep="") ##and include designation by half!
#but actually mostly group by strain&temp because this makes more sense for my design

# flag control wells
GCs <- GCs %>% filter(!is.na(OD)) %>% mutate(control = temperature == designation_for_control)

# zero all curves #this one, it makes sense to do by run/plate which also includes the half designation
# I removed a control variable since there is no control on each plate
GCs <- GCs %>% group_by(RRPP) %>% mutate(ODc0 = OD - median(OD[time < 0.5 ]))
GCs <- GCs %>% ungroup()

#remove manually flagged replicates - 009 & nt5076
GCs <- GCs %>% filter(!(strain=="NT5009"&temperature=="37"&replicate %in% c("2", "3")))
GCs <- GCs %>% filter(!(strain=="NT5076"&temperature=="37"&replicate %in% c("1")))
#009 was contam in those replicates
#NT5076 rep 1 37ºC there are some issue wells after ~16h

 # check between replicates #with the whole growth curve (no time cutoff)
GCsf <- GCs
GCsf <- GCsf %>% mutate(combi=paste(strain,temperature, sep='-'))

#37ºC
ggplot(GCsf %>% filter(temperature==37), aes(time, OD, group = RRPPRCC, color=as.factor(replicate))) +
  geom_line(alpha = 0.5) + facet_wrap(~strain) + theme(legend.position = "none")

#27ºC
ggplot(GCsf %>% filter(temperature==27), aes(time, OD, group = RRPPRCC, color=as.factor(replicate))) +
  geom_line(alpha = 0.5) + facet_wrap(~strain) + theme(legend.position = "none")

#is all the info still there?
dplyr::count((GCsf %>% group_by(strain)), temperature, control)

# Blank curves #this divides everything by the max 37ºC o.d. #which more or less puts everything on the same scale, between strains
#no time cutoff to maintain 'full' AUC
tmp <- GCsf %>% group_by(temperature, strain) %>% summarize(median37=median(ODc0[ time == max(time) & control ]))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'temperature'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.
tmp <- tmp[which(!is.na(tmp$median37)),c(2:3)] #just keep the ctrl medians
tmp2 <- full_join(GCsf, tmp) 
## Joining, by = "strain"
tmp2$ODc01 <- tmp2$ODc0/tmp2$median37 #normalizes all O.D. values to the median 37 OD
GCsf <- tmp2

GCsf <-  GCsf %>% group_by(RRPPRCC) %>%
  mutate( ODc01b_scaled = (ODc01 - min(ODc01)) / abs(1 - min(ODc01)),
          ODc01b_shifted = ODc01 - min(ODc01),
          ODc0_scaled = (ODc0 - min(ODc0)) / abs(1 - min(ODc0)),
          ODc0_shifted = ODc0 - min(ODc0),) %>% ungroup()

#re-plot the blanked data to check it 
ggplot(GCsf %>% filter(temperature==37), aes(time, ODc0_scaled, group = RRPPRCC, color=as.factor(replicate))) +
  geom_line(alpha = 0.5) + facet_wrap(~strain) + theme(legend.position = "none")

ggplot(GCsf %>% filter(temperature==27), aes(time, ODc01b_scaled, group = RRPPRCC, color=as.factor(replicate))) +
  geom_line(alpha = 0.5) + facet_wrap(~strain) + theme(legend.position = "none")

# Calculate AUCs
#on the 'full' data - no time cutoff but normalized to 37ºC
AUCs <- GCsf %>% group_by(RRPPRCC, strain, replicate, temperature, control) %>%
  summarise(
    AUC_scaled = calcAUC(ODc01b_scaled, time),
    AUC_shifted = calcAUC(ODc01b_shifted, time)) 
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'RRPPRCC', 'strain', 'replicate',
## 'temperature'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.
#normalize to 37º control
#grouped by replicate because reps were done at the same time (~week/month)
AUCs37 <- AUCs[which(AUCs$control==TRUE),]
AUCs37 <- AUCs37 %>% group_by(strain, replicate) %>% summarise(AUC_scaled37=median(AUC_scaled),
                                                    AUC_shifted37=median(AUC_shifted))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'strain'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.
AUCs2 <- full_join(AUCs,AUCs37)
## Joining, by = c("strain", "replicate")
AUCs2$normAUC_scaled <- AUCs2$AUC_scaled/AUCs2$AUC_scaled37
AUCs2$normAUC_shifted <- AUCs2$AUC_shifted/AUCs2$AUC_shifted37

AUCs2$normAUC <- ifelse( abs(AUCs2$normAUC_scaled - 1) < abs(AUCs2$normAUC_shifted - 1),
                         AUCs2$normAUC_scaled, AUCs2$normAUC_shifted )

#check these differences too by histogram #now the reps are really consistent / normal at 37
ggplot(AUCs2 %>% filter(temperature==37), aes(x=normAUC_shifted, group = RRPPRCC, color=as.factor(replicate))) +
  geom_histogram(alpha = 0.5) + facet_wrap(~strain) + theme(legend.position = "none")
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

# Check overall data by temperature
ggplot(AUCs2 %>% filter(temperature %in% c(27,37)), aes(x=as.factor(temperature), y=normAUC, group=replicate, color = as.factor(replicate)))+
  geom_point() +
  facet_wrap(~strain) +
  theme_bw(base_size = 12) + theme(legend.position = "none")
## Warning: Removed 144 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

#median AUCs
medianAUCsnorm <- AUCs2 %>% group_by(strain, temperature, replicate) %>%
  summarise(normAUC = median(normAUC))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'strain', 'temperature'. You can override
## using the `.groups` argument.
medianAUCsnorm <- medianAUCsnorm[which(medianAUCsnorm$temperature!=47),] 

#tidy results with tidyr
medianAUCs_tidynorm <- medianAUCsnorm %>% tidyr::spread(temperature, normAUC)
#write.csv(medianAUCs_tidynorm, "Results/AUCs_normbyrep_median_tidy2_24hcutoff.csv")
medianAUCs_tidynorm
